“The engaging courses I have completed during my time at WKU have helped prepare me for life beyond the classroom. They have inspired and motivated me to incorporate creativity and critical thinking in all aspects of my life. My professors over the years have also been monumental to my successes by challenging me to do my best and providing encouragement along the way." Hadley Rouse is a senior majoring in Vocal Music from Owensboro, KY. She’ll be performing her piece, “tears Breaking On Glass” during the 47th Annual Student Research Conference this Saturday, March 25. The campus and community are invited to attend this free event. Learn more at wku.edu/studentresearch. #PeopleofWKU #WKU (Photo courtesy Puppet Animation Scotland.)

“This project is important to me because it offers a connection between social justice and academic research. I feel as though we are in a cultural and political transition, and there are many socio-cultural groups that are facing particular hardships. A project such as this shows that, even in the most dire circumstances, pockets of hope exist and thrive. These findings offer us a road towards social, economic, and cultural sustainability.” Elizabeth Willenbrink is a WKU Graduate student presenting her research project, “Cultivating Community: Food Insecurity and Community Gardening Among African Refugees in Bowling Green, KY,” at the 47th Annual Student Research Conference this Saturday, March 25. The event is free and open to the public. Learn more at wku.edu/studentresearch. #PeopleofWKU

“Very few high school students get access to quality business classes.  Not only have I taken college-level business courses in addition to my STEM classes, but I am able to do a research project that sets me apart from everyone else in the world.  It has been a humbling process. I’ve realized that what I know now barely scratches the surface of the wealth of information out there.” Dylan Daugherty is a senior at the @gattonacademy from Madisonville, KY, researching Finance. He is presenting his research project, “The Effect of Financial Literacy on Preventative Healthcare Usage” at the 47th annual Student Research Conference this Saturday, March 25. The campus and community are invited to attend this free event. Learn more at wku.edu/studentresearch. \n#PeopleofWKU #WKU
